default2. Does the UK’s innovation policy place sufficient focus on applied R&amp;D and exploitation?default&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUK innovation policy under successive Governments has not fully recognised the different R&amp;D models under which the UK’s high tech industries 
defaultoperate. This has led to funding streams generally following the R&amp;D model required by the pharmaceutical industry – one that has a proportionally large investment in research – over the model required by the engineering industries – with a proportionally 
defaultlarge investment in development. The imbalance of annual 
defaultfunding between Research Councils – c.£3bn – and the Technology Strategy Board
default (TSB)
default – under £400m – demonstrates this.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs 
defaultdepicted
default in Figure 1 below, the focus on research in the pharmaceutical ind
defaultustry is far great
defaulter than the developmental stage. In contrast, the innovation model in 
defaultindustrie
defaults such as aerospace or defence 
defaultrequire
defaults
default a much 
defaultfar 
defaultgreater investment in 
defaultthe design and 
defaultdevelopment
default phases
default. Unlike the pharmaceutical R&amp;D model, the aerospace 
defaultand defence industries rely on large scale demonstrators for the development of their products, taking
default laboratory research through costly technology development and manufacturing 
defaultdevelopment phases. 
defaultLikewise, as the equipment being produced through the eng
defaultineering R&amp;D model is safety critical, demonstrators are vital in testing components both individually and connected, throu
defaultghout the manufacturing process.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 7-8
default time
default greater Government funding for Research Councils relative to the TSB means that the UK
default government
default limited
default R&amp;D grants and funding are far more likely to support research-intensive innovation and provide insufficient support to industries with development-intensive innovation models.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 1 – R&amp;D models differ by sectordefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis bias towards research-intensive R&amp;D processes is reinforced by the UK’s corporate tax regime. As noted above, the UK is not globally competitive in-terms of supporting R&amp;D and capital investment through the tax regime.  Incentives that do exist within
default the regime, in particular the new Patent Box, also have an in-built bias towards certain types of innovation models. By providing a discounted corporate tax rate on income generated from patents, the Patent Box provides benefits to products with low-techn
defaultological complexity and shallow innovation supply-chains (albeit with high scientific and research complexity). 
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor example, once a drug has been proven, it is relatively easy to patent and produce, and so to identify 
defaultincome 
defaultgenerated from a patent for t
defaultax purposes. It is far more complicated to identify the income generated from a patented technology embedded within an engine or aircraft. 
